{{Other uses|Moly (disambiguation){{!}}Moly}}
[[Image:Snowdrop Galanthus elwesii.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Galanthus|Snowdrop]], perhaps the herb ''moly'']]
'''Moly''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: {{lang|grc|μῶλυ}}, {{IPA-el|môly|}}) is a magical herb mentioned in book 10 of [[Homer]]'s ''[[Odyssey]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=681}} cites: Homer, ''Odyssey'', x. 302–306.</ref>

==In Greek Myth==
In the story the Odyssey, [[Hermes]] gave this herb to [[Odysseus]] to protect him from [[Circe]]'s wizardry when he went to her home to rescue his friends.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=681}} These friends came together with him from the island Aiolos after they escaped from the Laestrigonians. 

According to the ''"New History"'' of [[Ptolemy Hephaestion]] (according to [[Photius]]) the plant mentioned by Homer grew from the blood of the [[Gigas (mythology)|Giant]]  killed on [[Circe]]'s island, by [[Helios]] ally of Circe. In this description the flower was white, and a derivation of the name was given, from the "hard" (Greek ''malos'') combat with the Giant.<ref>{{Citation|title=HELIUS : Greek Titan god of the sun | url = http://www.theoi.com/Titan/Helios.html}}</ref> 

Homer also describes Moly by saying "The root was black, while the flower was as white as milk; the gods call it Moly, Dangerous for a mortal man to pluck from the soil, but not for the deathless gods. All lies within their power".{{sfn|Homer|Butler|1898|loc=Book X}}

==Assignment to a real species==
There has been much controversy as to the identification. Philippe Champault decides in favour of the ''[[Peganum harmala]]'' (of the order Rutaceae),<ref>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=681}} cites: ''Phéniciens et Grecs en Italie d'après l'Odyssée'' (1906), pp.&nbsp;504 seq.</ref> the Syrian or African rue (Greek {{lang|grc|πἠγανον}}), from the husks of which the vegetable alkaloid [[harmaline]] is extracted. The flowers are white with green stripes. Victor Bérard relying partly on a Semitic root,<ref>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=681}} cites: Victor Bérard ''Les Phéniciens et l'Odyssee'', ii. 288 seq.</ref> prefers the ''[[Atriplex halimus]]'' (''atriplex'', a Latin form of Greek {{lang|grc|ἀτράφαξυς}}, and {{lang|grc|ἅλιμος}}, marine), order Chenopodiaceae, a herb or low shrub common on the south European coasts. These identifications are noticed by R. M. Henry,<ref name=Chisholm-Henry>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=681}} cites: R. M. Henry ''Class. Rev.'' (Dec. 1906), p.&nbsp;434.</ref> who illustrates the Homeric account by passages in the Paris and Leiden [[magical papyri]], and argues that moly is probably a magical name, derived perhaps from Phoenician or Egyptian sources, for a plant which cannot be certainly identified. He shows that the "difficulty of pulling up" the plant is not a merely physical one, but rather connected with the peculiar powers claimed by magicians.<ref name=Chisholm-Henry/> 

Medical historians have speculated that the transformation to pigs was not intended literally but refers to [[anticholinergic]] intoxication.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Andreas Plaitakis & Roger C. Duvoisin |title=Homer's moly identified as ''Galanthus nivalis'' L.: physiologic antidote to stramonium poisoning |journal=[[Clinical Neuropharmacology]] |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=1–5 |year=1983 |pmid=6342763 |doi=10.1097/00002826-198303000-00001}}</ref> Symptoms include [[amnesia]], [[hallucinations]], and [[delusions]] - this description of "moly" fits the [[snowdrop]], a [[flower]] of the region that contains [[galantamine]], which is an [[anticholinesterase]] and can therefore counteract anticholinergics.

==In other works==
*In [[Tennyson]]'s ''[[The Lotos-Eaters]]'', the moly is coupled with the [[amaranth]] ("propt on beds of amaranth and moly").{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=681}}
*[[Carl Linnaeus]] referenced the mythical plant with ''[[Allium moly]]'', the scientific name for golden garlic, though the perianth of this species is yellow, not white.

